

	 
      When you are old and gray and full of sleep,  And nodding by the fire, takedown this book,  And slowly read, and dream of the soft look  Your eyes had once, and of their shadows deep;    How many loved your moments of glad grace,  And love your beauty with love false or true;  But one man love the pilgrim soul in you,  And loved the sorrows of your changing face.    And bending down beside the glowing bars  Murmur, a little sad, From us fled Love;  He paced upon the mountains far above,  And his his face amid a crowd of stars.    W B Yeats 
    
